### `submit_transform_hypothesis`
REQUIRED before calling execute_python_solution. Submit a detailed natural language specification of the transformation rule you believe applies. This will be recorded and sent to an independent reviewer. Write it as if explaining to a programmer who must reimplement solve() from scratch using only your description.
**Input Schema**
```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "hypothesis": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "Exhaustive natural language specification of the transformation rule. Include: (1) high-level summary, (2) step-by-step algorithm, (3) all edge cases and conditional logic, (4) how the rule generalizes beyond training examples. A competent programmer should be able to fully reconstruct the solve() function from this description alone."
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "hypothesis"
  ]
}
```

### `execute_python_solution`
Run a COMPLETE self-contained Python submission that defines solve(grid). It will be executed against training examples and then used to predict test outputs. You MUST call submit_transform_hypothesis first in the same turn.
**Input Schema**
```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "code": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "Complete python code with solve(grid) function"
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "code"
  ]
}
```

### `run_code`
Run an isolated Python snippet for quick testing/debugging. Each call runs in a fresh environment (no variables persist across calls). Available globals: train_samples = list of {'input': grid, 'output': grid}; test_samples = list of {'input': grid}.
**Input Schema**
```json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "code": {
      "type": "string",
      "description": "Python code to execute"
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "code"
  ]
}
```
